Resource Distribution for Maximum Satisfaction



In a community welfare center, a coordinator is responsible for distributing snack packs to a group of children. Each child has a minimum satisfaction requirement, represented by an integer value. Each available snack pack also has a size, represented by another integer. A child will be satisfied only if the size of the snack pack assigned to them is greater than or equal to their minimum requirement. Each child can receive at most one snack pack, and each snack pack can be given to only one child. 



Your task is to determine the maximum number of children who can be satisfied by distributing the available snack packs in the best possible way.

Input format :
The first line contains an integer n — the number of children.
The second line contains n space-separated integers representing the minimum satisfaction requirement of each child.
The third line contains an integer m — the number of snack packs available.
The fourth line contains m space-separated integers representing the size of each snack pack.
Output format :
Print a single integer representing the maximum number of satisfied children.




Code constraints :
1≤n,m≤105

1≤g[i],s[j]≤105

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
3
1 2 3
2
1 1
Output 1 :
1
Input 2 :
2
1 2
3
1 2 3
Output 2 :
2



#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;

    vector<int> g(n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> g[i];
    }

    int m;
    cin >> m;

    vector<int> s(m);
    for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        cin >> s[i];
    }

    sort(g.begin(), g.end());
    sort(s.begin(), s.end());

    int i = 0; // child
    int j = 0; // snack
    int count = 0;

    while (i < n && j < m) {

        // snack satisfies child
        if (s[j] >= g[i]) {
            count++;
            i++;
            j++;
        }
        else {
            // snack too small
            j++;
        }
    }

    cout << count;

    return 0;
}
